SIMPLE: coarctate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Coarctate
<hw>Co*arc"tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>
}</mhw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Coarctate</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To press together; to crowd; to
straiten; to confine closely.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To restrain; to confine.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Ayliffe.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Coarctate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Coarctate
<hw>Co*arc"tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>coarctatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>coarctare</ets> to press together;
<ets>co-</ets> + <ets>arctare</ets> to press together, from
<ets>arctus</ets>, p. p. See <er>Arctation</er>.]</ety>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Pressed together; closely connected; -- applied
to insects having the abdomen separated from the thorax only by a
constriction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Coarctate pupa</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a pupa
closely covered by the old larval skin, as in most
Diptera.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Coarctation</ent>⟦br⟧
